The paper discusses a neurally-plausible memory representation for use in artificial intelligence, specifically in learning to play a video game. This suggests that the paper is likely to fall under the categories of neural networks (cs.NE), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), and machine learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper discusses the potential applications of the proposed memory representation in reinforcement learning, which falls under the category of control systems (cs.SY). Finally, the paper uses a video game environment to demonstrate the utility of the proposed method, which suggests that it may also fall under the category of computer vision (cs.CV).
